  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you are selling an apartment or townhouse in Brisbane, your buyer's solicitor will almost certainly order a body corporate records search before they advise their client to go unconditional. This search is not a formality. It is a detailed investigation into the scheme's financial health, governance history, and any outstanding issues that could affect the buyer's decision or the price they are willing to pay. Sellers who have never read their own records often learn things during a sale campaign that they wish they had known months earlier.</p>

      <p>Understanding what a records search reveals, what buyers look for in those documents, and how to get ahead of any issues before you list is one of the more underused advantages available to apartment sellers in Brisbane's inner east.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a body corporate records search actually covers</h2>
      <p>A records search in Queensland is a formal request made under the Body Corporate and Community Management Act. It gives the buyer's solicitor access to a comprehensive package of documents from the scheme's manager or the body corporate committee. The search typically covers meeting minutes from the last two to three years, financial statements, levy registers, insurance certificates, correspondence, maintenance records, the sinking fund forecast, the administrative fund balance, and any current or pending disputes.</p>

      <p>Each of these documents tells a story. Meeting minutes reveal whether the committee is actively managing the building or whether maintenance issues are being deferred. Financial statements show whether levies are keeping pace with running costs or whether the scheme has been underfunded. Levy registers show whether individual lot owners are in arrears. The sinking fund forecast, which is prepared by a quantity surveyor and projects major capital expenditure over a 10-year horizon, tells buyers whether future works are funded or whether a special levy is likely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Red flags buyers look for in the records</h2>
      <p>Experienced buyers and their conveyancers know exactly what to look for. A low sinking fund balance relative to the building's age and the forecast capital expenditure is a reliable warning sign. Older Brisbane apartment buildings that have deferred maintenance on items like lifts, pool equipment, roofing, or common area electrical systems face the prospect of a special levy, which is a one-off capital call on all lot owners to fund work that the sinking fund cannot cover. Buyers price this risk into their offers, and often discount significantly when the records are unclear about funding adequacy.</p>

      <p>Ongoing disputes are another area buyers scrutinise closely. A dispute with a contractor over defect remediation, a complaint lodged with the Office of the Commissioner for Body Corporate and Community Management, or a pattern of unresolved agenda items across multiple meetings all raise questions about the quality of governance. None of these necessarily kill a sale, but they do affect buyer confidence, which affects price.</p>

      <p>Outstanding defects, particularly in schemes that are fewer than 10 years old, are a specific concern. If a developer defect has been reported in the minutes but not yet resolved, buyers want to understand whether the builder is engaged on rectification or whether the body corporate is facing litigation. Insurance details also matter: buyers check that the replacement value and the insurer are appropriate for the building.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers should order their own search before listing</h2>
      <p>Ordering a records search on your own scheme before you list costs a few hundred dollars and takes a few days. The benefit is that you read the same documents your buyer will read, before your buyer reads them. If the sinking fund is healthy, the levies are current, the minutes are unremarkable, and there are no pending disputes, that is a selling point you can present with confidence. A well-run body corporate is genuinely valuable to buyers and worth highlighting in your campaign materials.</p>

      <p>If the records reveal a problem, knowing early gives you options. If a special levy has been resolved in principle but is not yet formally documented, you can follow up with the body corporate manager to ensure the minutes are current before the buyer's search is completed. If there is a maintenance item that has been deferred, you can understand whether it affects your lot specifically or is a common area concern, and brief your agent accordingly so they can address buyer questions factually rather than evasively.</p>

      <p>What you cannot do is control the records themselves. You cannot remove an outstanding defect from the minutes, settle a dispute before it is settled, or improve the sinking fund balance in the weeks before you list. What you can control is your knowledge of the situation and how clearly and accurately you communicate it to buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Presenting a well-run body corporate as a selling point</h2>
      <p>Most apartment buyers in Brisbane's inner east have encountered at least one scheme with poor governance or underfunded maintenance. When the records are clean, experienced buyers notice. Consistently well-attended meetings, a sinking fund balance that tracks ahead of the forecast, current insurance, and no outstanding disputes signal that the scheme is being managed properly. This reduces the perceived risk of ownership and supports confident offers.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be in a position to brief prospective buyers on the headline financials in broad terms during the campaign, before the formal due diligence period. Knowing the quarterly levy, the sinking fund balance per lot, and the approximate age of the last major capital works gives buyers useful context and reduces the anxiety that often accompanies the records review period. Buyers who feel informed and comfortable tend to make cleaner, less conditional offers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can and cannot control before sale</h2>
      <p>As an individual lot owner, your influence over the body corporate is real but limited. You can attend general meetings and vote on resolutions. You can raise maintenance concerns formally through the committee. You can ensure your own levies are current and that no arrears appear against your lot in the records. These are the actions within your control, and they matter.</p>

      <p>What you cannot unilaterally control is the overall financial position of the scheme, whether other lot owners are in arrears, or whether a longstanding maintenance dispute gets resolved before your sale campaign. These factors are part of the reality of strata title property ownership, and buyers in Brisbane's inner-east apartment market generally understand that. What they respond to is an informed seller who can discuss the scheme's situation clearly and honestly, rather than one who is visibly surprised by their own records search.</p>

